---
import Site from "@/layouts/Site.astro";

export const prerender = false;
---

<Site title="About — Lighthouse" pageHeading="What is Lighthouse?"
      pageSubhead="A canonical reference for AI agents — find the right doc, fast, then jump to the original.">
  <article class="max-w-2xl mt-8 chunk-prose">
    <p>
      Lighthouse is a retrieval engine over public reference material — IETF
      RFCs, OWASP, NIST SP-800, framework documentation, and recognised
      practitioner writing. Sources are crawled under permissive licences,
      chunked, embedded, summarised, and indexed in a Postgres + pgvector
      store. An MCP endpoint exposes a single <code>search</code> tool any
      agent can wire up; search results link out to the original publisher.
    </p>

    <h2>Why a finder, not a republisher</h2>
    <p>
      Even on permissive licences, hosting full text behind a subscription
      makes us a content middleman. We don't want that. We retrieve
      enough text to identify the right doc — title, summary, topic
      keywords, a few lines of context — and send you to the source.
      The AI agent gets a precise pointer; the original publisher keeps
      the traffic.
    </p>

    <h2>How retrieval works</h2>
    <p>
      Every chunk has three text fields beyond the body: a Qwen-7B
      one-sentence summary, 3–5 topic tags, and 6–12 search-relevant
      keywords (synonyms and alternative phrasings). Search runs BM25
      over a weighted tsvector (summary &amp; keywords A, tags B,
      content C) and cosine similarity over the chunk embedding.
      A reciprocal-rank-fusion merge passes the top candidates through
      a gpt-4o-mini reranker that scores each against the query
      directly. The winner is what you see at top of /search.
    </p>

    <h2>How it differs from Context7</h2>
    <p>
      Context7 ships a wide library-doc snapshot — hundreds of framework
      docs, thousands of snippets each. Lighthouse is narrower on
      library docs (the most-used per role) and adds three layers
      Context7 doesn't index: canonical standards (RFCs, OWASP, NIST),
      practitioner literature, and post-cutoff streams (RSS feeds,
      release notes). Where the two overlap, our bet is depth via
      summarisation; where they don't, we're the only place to find it.
    </p>

    <h2>Built in the open</h2>
    <p>
      The code lives at
      <a href="https://github.com/ElMundiUA/lighthouse" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com/ElMundiUA/lighthouse</a>
      under Apache 2.0. The corpus index is hosted; the retrieval
      engine is open. Self-host a copy for your team if you'd rather
      run your own.
    </p>

    <h2>Subscribing</h2>
    <p>
      Anonymous access has a small daily query budget so you can
      evaluate. Signed-in readers get more. A paid tier (Pro) lifts the
      cap meaningfully and unlocks per-team features. See <a href="/pricing">pricing</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Site>
